Am DLR werden an vielen Instituten immer wieder gleiche oder √§hnliche Daten gekauft, erfasst und/oder archiviert.
Eine zentrale - in unserem Fall - Geodateninfrastruktur wie sie z.B. aktuell und weiterhin im Projekt "Digitaler Atlas" erstellt wird, w√§re ein wichtiger Ansatz.
Das Problem ist, dass immer nach Ende eines Projekts keine (langfristigen) Mittel mehr zur Verf√ºgung stehen und alles dort entwickelte verschwindet mit den Forschern, die nur wenige-Jahres-Vertr√§ge f√ºr einzelne Projekte bekommen. Diese kurzsichtige Denkweise steht somit zusammen mit der Forderung nach hohen Drittmittelquoten jeder Art von nachhaltiger und langfristiger Nutzung von Daten, Software und Wissen kontr√§r entgegen.
Ziel muss also eine langfristige, nachhaltige Bereitstellung einer gepflegten Infrastruktur f√ºr die Langzeit-Archivierung und den zumindest f√ºr die gesamte Forschungseinrichtung offenen Langzeit-Zugriff auf Daten sein.
Das Problem bei zugrundeliegenden Originaldaten (z.B. Satellitenbilder oder Daten von Landesvermessungs√§mtern) ist die Nutzungs-Lizenz, die normalerweise nur f√ºr genau dieses eine Projekt besteht. Somit darf man diese nicht lokal nach Projektende speichern. Will man sp√§ter Forschungsarbeiten reproduzieren, muss man wieder eine Lizenz der Daten erwerben, erh√§lt aber meist nicht mehr die identischen Daten sondern eine reprozessierte oder neuere Version, mit der sich die Forschungsarbeiten oft nicht reproduzieren lassen.
Besteht hier eine M√∂glichkeit andere Lizenzvereinbarungen f√ºr die langfristige Sicherstellung von Forschungsergebnissen zu erhalten?
Neben der Technik und einer nachhaltigen Infrastruktur ist aber auch das Zusammenbringen der Forscher, die bestimmte Arten von Daten an vielen verschiedenen Instituten und aus vielen verschiedenen Richtungen wichtig, die oft nichts voneinander wissen.

The problem with collecting research data is the same as digitalization in research groups and any other barriers - if the group leader does not see this as a necessary and valuable task, he/she will not enforce it and it will most likely not be done (since it costs a lot of time and effort).

SERVC1_other: Personal and Time. Who is supposed to do all that?
SERVC3: It is an illusion to think that what scientist are lacking are tools or more workshops. It all comes down to personal and time to do any documentation or metadata collection. The only thing that matters and allows a scientist to exist in the job continues to be publication and first or last authorship position on the publication. Any documentation that exceeds this purpose, unfortunately, is a waste of time. As far as sharing of raw data is concerned, aside of legal issues when working with human subject data, making data open access means scientific suicide: As own publications are the only thing ultimately maintaining a scientists job, anyone who lets others analyze data without forcing them to involve oneself on a lead position is, again unfortunately, a fool. No scientist receives any budget for personal or consumables because of documenting metadata systematically or for sharing data open access. This is not good or in the interest of the public that funds all our research, but this is the political design of the system. As long as there is no substantial change to that, there will never be any truly meaningful success in open access, shared, metadata documented, data repositories.

SERVC1_other: With unlimited money, we could have some people doing this full time or if I had a permanent employment as technician instead of aiming for publications there would be time to build up such systems. Our research group is 15 people including PhD students, and the experiments are not much using big-facility hardware or software that anyone else could take care of without our domain expertise
SERVC3: I don't feel that some initiatives to create completely computer-understandable metadata-taxonomies seem meaningful (e.g. listing "voltage" as something that can be measured, which is anyway not meaningful without a full human-readable drawing of the experiment and circuit scheme to know what kind of signal is being measured). But I think there is room for some general suggestions/advice/tools/standards for keeping track of related files, metadata and (especially) processing steps of a not-automated pipeline. Example: We use facility-provided network storage for where big raw-data can be written by a specific computer handling a spectrometer (within a directory with ID-number based on scheduled beamtimes), but metadata like parameters of laser are written to a different kind of network storage (due to rules about write-access and the mere need to be able to write such data also when no beamtime is scheduled in the cumbersome beamtime-management system). And then some things are logged manually in a wiki-style web page. Then during data analysis you need to find the two directories from the same date on different storage platforms, and the web page for that day. And when making an analysis script to produce output files (an ad-hoc processing pipeline) it would be nice to have a system for getting the adjustable parameters of that script saved together with the output. If Jupyter Notebooks are used to run the script they could be manually saved, but if there are some parameters left at default values they are not seen in the script... so I'm more thinking that for a text or binay file would accompany each output file, or for file formats like HDF5 it could be part of the output file, but possibly a web system that allows searching for all raw- and output- files by data and keywords/metadata like sample-name or laser-parameters could have been nice (if all the system integration of making acquisition softwares and analysis softwares provide it the data, have IDs or timestamps to know which things are related...)...
